Hereâ€™s a list of 25 commonly used Docker commands along with their descriptions:

docker --version:
Displays the installed Docker version.

docker pull <image>:
Downloads a Docker image from a registry (usually Docker Hub).

docker run <image>:
Runs a container based on the specified image.

docker ps:
Lists all running containers.

docker ps -a:
Lists all containers, including stopped ones.

docker images:
Lists all downloaded Docker images.

docker build <path>:
Builds a Docker image from a Dockerfile located in the specified path.

docker stop <container_id>:
Stops a running container.

docker start <container_id>:
Starts a stopped container.

docker rm <container_id>:
Removes a stopped container.

docker rmi <image_id>:
Removes a Docker image.

docker exec -it <container_id> <command>:
Executes a command inside a running container (e.g., bash for a terminal).

docker logs <container_id>:
Displays the logs from a running or stopped container.

docker inspect <container_id>:
Shows detailed information about a container or image, such as configuration and networking.

docker commit <container_id> <new_image_name>:
Creates a new image from a container's current state.

docker network ls:
Lists all Docker networks.

docker network create <network_name>:
Creates a new Docker network.

docker network connect <network_name> <container_id>:
Connects a container to a specific network.

docker volume ls:
Lists all Docker volumes.

docker volume create <volume_name>:
Creates a new Docker volume.

docker-compose up:
Starts containers defined in a docker-compose.yml file.

docker-compose down:
Stops and removes containers, networks, and volumes created by docker-compose up.

docker tag <image> <repository:tag>:
Tags a local image with a new name and tag.

docker push <repository:tag>:
Pushes an image to a Docker registry.

docker container prune:
Removes all stopped containers.

docker restart <container_id>:
Restarts a running or stopped container.

docker stats:
Displays real-time statistics (CPU, memory, I/O usage) of running containers.

docker top <container_id>:
Shows the running processes inside a container.

docker diff <container_id>:
Shows the changes made to the filesystem of a container.

docker history <image>:
Displays the history of a Docker image (all the layers and their corresponding commands).

docker attach <container_id>:
Attaches to a running container, allowing you to interact with its terminal.

docker cp <container_id>:<path_inside_container> <path_on_host>:
Copies files or directories from a container to the host or vice versa.

docker export <container_id> > <filename.tar>:
Exports the filesystem of a container as a tar archive.

docker import <filename.tar>:
Imports a tarball to create a Docker image.

docker login:
Logs into a Docker registry (e.g., Docker Hub) from the command line.

docker logout:
Logs out from a Docker registry.

docker save -o <filename.tar> <image>:
Saves a Docker image as a tar archive file.

docker load -i <filename.tar>:
Loads a Docker image from a tar archive file.

docker rename <old_name> <new_name>:
Renames a container.

docker system df:
Displays disk usage for Docker (images, containers, volumes, etc.).
